{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ed2d8dc0-2a36-4e59-a885-ab349a2edad8","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). With the official `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, that's `builder.Services.AddMcpServer().WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n- **Don't write to stdout** for logging — use stderr instead, or stdout will corrupt the MCP protocol messages.\n- You can also add `\"env\": { ... }` for environment variables if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"19c8f77a-0a51-41db-adc1-68b3d01b6583","outputTokens":285,"requestId":"7FD2:3B9822:4580794:4C13E09:69F15AFB"},"id":"e4b1c3a1-8c09-4e94-9577-08186280fd78","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:12:36.370Z","parentId":"c59e6856-a2f6-4f91-91ef-9e21e6094a5a"}
